data.label:
Narrator

I had been invited to an exclusive preview of Alfred Kcirbuk's new film, "The Morning Shall Come".

Narrator

With its massive budget and Kcirbuk's directorial cachet, this drama was set to be a milestone for Sordland's burgeoning film scene. Personally, though, I was just looking forward to spending some time with my family.

Narrator

Serge had maxed out the air conditioning to keep the Kadilla comfortable. I kept silent through most of our ride on the H-1. I couldn't get my mind off the results of the Assembly vote.

Narrator

I gazed at the vast plains between Holsord and Erlory as we drove on the H-1. Serge had maxed out the air conditioning to keep the Kadilla comfortable.

Franc

"Look what you've done, Deana..."

Narrator

Deana looked down.

Player

"I know, I know. I didn't mean to make her sad..."

Player

"You are right. I'm sorry for lashing out."

Franc

"Not again..."

Narrator

Serge rolled down the soundproof glass between us.

Monica

"Really? You were *joking*?"

Narrator

Franc turned toward us for the first time since he'd gotten in the car.

Narrator

In the distance, there were several planes flying towards the city.

Serge Wolkner

"Oh, sir, I don't mind the young mister. He's an intelligent young man."

Player

"It's just behind those hills. We should go there sometime."

Franc

"I know. Why lie? The truth always sounds better anyway."

Player

"Are you sure about that, son? Truth doesn't really sell."

Monica

"Come on. Let's get out."

Narrator

Serge opened the doors, and we exited onto the red carpet.

Narrator

In contrast with the cinema's baroque-style exterior, the inside was modern and sleek, with bare walls painted in black, red and white.

Narrator

Serge opened the doors, and we exited onto the red carpet.

Narrator

On the wall next to the entrance, there were painted the words "Stop The Oppression of Bluds".

Narrator

Other graffiti next to it read, "Stop the Genocide in Wehlen" and "Axis of Evil: Smolak, Rayne, Lancea."

Policeman

"Excuse us, Mr. President."

Player_Italic

I followed along, silently.

Player

"Don't touch me again."

Policeman

"Everything is for your safety, sir."

Narrator

We were just about to enter the building when a journalist managed to block the path.

Alfred Kcirbuk

"Madame! Mr. President! It's so good to see you here."

Narrator

He gently bowed at Monica and shook our hands.

Player

"The honor is mine, Mr. Kcirbuk. I'm a big fan of your work."

Alfred Kcirbuk

"That's by Mikel Vargas, Mr. President. It beat my film The Sordish Dream for the top prize at the Benfi Festival last year."

Narrator

Although I wasn't in much of a moviegoing mood, it would have been unpresidential not to attend.

Franc

"Since when do you care what's happening in my life?"

Player

"I've been busy lately, but I'll always have time for you."

Narrator

I noticed Franc fidgeting with his tie anxiously.

Player

"Excited for the movie?"

Franc

"Busy with failure?"

Monica

"Franc, don't talk to your father that way! He tried his best."

Franc

"What an honor, Your Highness."

Monica

"Franc, don't talk to your father that way! He's been working so hard for this country."

Player

"Are you having a good time, sweetie?"

Narrator

Deana nodded happily.

Deana

"What about you, Papa? You won something, right? You should smile! And keep doing your best even if you lose."

Deana

"Don't worry about me, Papa! You've got the whole country to worry about!"

Player

"All I'm worried about is whether or not there will be popcorn."

Deana

"From you!"

Monica

"How should I know? I don't meddle in these affairs."

Player

"Now, no more politics talk! Isn't that right, Monica?"

Monica

"Oh, you've made sure of that."

Monica

"Anton you can't act like this with us. I'm not your assistant."

Player

"Darling, we've been through this. I'm sorry."

Monica

"Great! We will!"

Player

"Who?"

Alfred Kcirbuk

"My producers told me you had expressed admiration for my work."

Narrator

We entered the screening room, the lights dimmed, and the film began.

Narrator

Tarquin Soll leaned on his cane. He had the same frail appearance I'd noticed at the Assembly meeting. Yet up close, I could still sense the raw magnetism that had kept him in power for 20 years.

Player

"What the hell were you doing at the Assembly vote, Mr. Soll?"

Tarquin Soll

"A man's got to get off his island every once in a while, you know."

Tarquin Soll

"My country was about to make a rash decision. I couldn't simply sit by."

Player

"It's not *your* country anymore."

Player

"You've succeeded, for now. But you won't be able to stop me for long."

Tarquin Soll

"No?"

Player

"Enjoy that power while it lasts."

Player

"It's not *your* country anymore."

Player

"I can handle Sordland without you, old man."

Tarquin Soll

"No?"

Tarquin Soll

"I wouldn't be so sure about that."

Player

"You may still have your loyalists. But I'm the one in control."

Player

"I'm happy you're looking out for me. But I don't need any help."

Tarquin Soll

"I was wrong to champion you all those years ago. You proved to be a spineless weasel!"

Player

"History will show who's what, Colonel."

Player

"You bastard!"

Tarquin Soll

"Now, if you'll excuse me, I've got my garden to get back to. Someone has to keep the weeds from spreading."

Player

"And are you pleased with the outcome?"

Tarquin Soll

"Threats don't suit you, Anton."

Tarquin Soll

"Quite."

Player

"You won't get away with your meddling."

Player

"A true president knows when he must step down."

Player

"But why did you block my reforms?"

Player

"Why do you want these reforms blocked so badly?"

Player

"Your cronies can't help you now."

Tarquin Soll

"I will not let you and that bleeding-heart idiot Ricter tarnish my precious Constitution."

Player

"Your Constitution is ancient history. My reforms will bring Sordland into the future."

Player

"You tarnished it enough for the both of us already."

Narrator

Some of his spittle landed on my cheek.

Tarquin Soll

"Ha!"

Tarquin Soll

"Ha!"

Player

"I know, but I need him on my side to undo your damage."

Player

"I am."

Player

"I'm no saint. But I'm trying to act for the good of the country."

Tarquin Soll

"You'll find out soon enough how your country repays you for your 'goodness'."

Narrator

I stormed past him and out the door.

Tarquin Soll

"I've known it since you opposed me all those years ago. You spineless backstabbing weasel!"

Tarquin Soll

"I've known it since you turned down the position I offered you all those years ago. You spineless weasel!"

Tarquin Soll

"You took the court's advice and extended the state of emergency. Very prudent."

Player

"Anything to keep my enemies at bay."

Player

"I'm surprised to see you here, sir."

Player

"I'm surprised to see you're still around, sir. What were you doing at the Assembly?"

Tarquin Soll

"I'm right about him, the same way I was right never to trust you. You spineless weasel!"

Tarquin Soll

"You have no idea what it takes to do this job, boy. But you'll find out soon enough."

Player

"At last, I can admit it: I never did like you."

Player

"I still have immense respect for you, Colonel. I wish it was reciprocated."

Player

"The Assembly considers me worthy. Doesn't that count for anything?"

Tarquin Soll

"If Sordland remains in your hands, the only future I see is misery."

Player

"There's nothing you can do anymore, old man."

Player

"Well-spoken as always. We'll see how well it serves you during your trial."

Tarquin Soll

"I wouldn't be so sure about that."

Tarquin Soll

"Banning the Young Sords, while the communists and Bludish scum run rampant?"

Tarquin Soll

"Why did you end the state of emergency so prematurely?"

Player

"Do you see me as your puppet?"

Player

"I see."

Player

"You could have spoken to me directly."

Player

"The country still needs to be brought out of recession. This was a distraction."

Player

"I judged that the worst of the threat was over."

Player

"It was reflecting badly on my reputation as a democratic leader."

Player

"It was a hard decision, but I did what I had to."

Player

"I wanted to stop the violence. They were the worst offenders."

Player

"They had to be punished for Circas' murder."

Player

"My decisions are not your business."

Tarquin Soll

"Your decision not to ban the Workers Party of Bludia may cause problems, however. They clearly are a continuation of the Bludish Freedom Front."

Player

"A ban will only lead to further violence."

Narrator

He raised his eyebrows.

Player

"What do you mean?"

Tarquin Soll

"How do you think I've been spending my retirement? Just tending to my garden in my island?"

Tarquin Soll

"I told Hawker you could be counted on to make the right choice."

Player

"The police are doing enough to keep the Bludish in line."

Player

"The police are already doing enough to keep the communists in line."

Player

"The Bludish were your problem, not mine."

Tarquin Soll

"And what good would that have done? You haven't trusted me since the Party Congress."

Player

"I always looked up to you. Just give me a chance to do my job."

Tarquin Soll

"I'm happy to hear that."

Tarquin Soll

"Next time, perhaps I will."

Tarquin Soll

"I see you as a novice in need of some valuable guidance."

Player

"You can trust me."

Player

"You had your chance to lead. Everyone saw what a mess you made."

Player

"I'm warning you, sir. Stay out of my presidency.

Reporter

"Your constitutional reforms made it through the Assembly -- how do you feel about their chances with the Supreme Court?"

Reporter

"Thank you, Mr. President. And were you aware that Tarquin Soll would be present at the proceedings?"

Reporter

"You recently rescinded your emergency declaration. Do you feel that the state has achieved its goals?"

Player

"Our enemies are still out there. But we cannot keep living in fear."

Player

"Declaring the emergency was a mistake. The country's back on the right path now."

Reporter

"One more question. Can you comment on the arrests of Marcel Koronti and Walter Tusk following the state takeovers of their companies?"

Reporter

"One more question. Can you comment on the arrest of Marcel Koronti following the state takeover of his corporation?"

Reporter

"One more question. Can you comment on the arrest of Walter Tusk following the state takeover of his corporation?"

Reporter

"One more question..."

Player

"He got in my way."

Player

"An unfortunate casualty, but nationalization is the only way forward."

Player

"No, I have no comment."

Player

"They got in my way."

Player

"He got in my way."

Player

"I'm going to keep fighting for my changes. This isn't over yet."

Player

"I will respect the Assembly's decision."

Player

"Not very well, to be honest."

Player

"Of course I was."

Player

"No, I had to find out from my driver."

Player

"I refuse to discuss Colonel Soll at this time."

Player

"The court will vote my way if they know what's good for them."

Player

"One way or another, these reforms will pass."

Player

"Don't make me angry, Franc."

Narrator

Franc turned his head away to look outside the window.

Player

"*You* calling me a tyrant, of all people?"

Player

"You're hurting me, Franc."
